               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-295" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-295" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-295" type="surname" value="TORRY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-295" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES TORRY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the employ of John Miles, who trades as Hamilton, Adams, and Co., at 3, Paternoster Row—Stewart was their porter—on 8th October, about one o'clock, I was in the packing room, and saw Stewart at the end of the counter near the door, rolling up his bag—I could see that, it contained something—ho put it outside and left—I called Foale and Drummond, and was examined the bag and found two volumes of "Curtis's Greek Etymology"—that book was in stock—</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220071"></xptr>
               <p>the books were placed back in the bag in the same position—I communi<lb></lb>cated with my employers, and when I returned the bag was gone.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-296" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-296" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-296" type="surname" value="FOALE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-296" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT FOALE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clerk in the same firm—on 8th October Tony spoke to me, and I found two books in a bag—I cannot say whether these are them—I put it back, and Mr. Drummond watched it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-297" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-297" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-297" type="surname" value="DRUMMOND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-297" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS DRUMMOND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clerk to the same firm—I saw Mr. Torry examine the bag—I watched it, and saw Stewart stand opposite it about two minutes—I then went to my desk, and heard him go out—I then, looked, and the bug was gone—he was away ten or fifteen minutes, long enough to go to Messrs. Ascher's, but not long enough to go there and back—I then saw him pass through the room; he had nothing in his hands then.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-298" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-298" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-298" type="surname" value="CRUNDELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-298" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN CRUNDELL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of Messrs. Ascher, publishers, of Bedford Street, Covent Garden—Ellis was their collector—Stewart was in their employ some time ago, but not at the same time as Ellis—this is Eliis's collecting-book—here is an entry in it: "8th October, Curtis's Principles of Greek Etymology, 2 vols. price 30<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>."—that 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. is in Eliis's writing; he put it down after he took the books—I had given him—5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to buy books that day—11<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. was not a proper price to pay for those two books, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. was the price—I saw aim when he came back, and he charged 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> Messrs. Ascher have not prosecuted him for embezzling the money—they made no complaint—they had every satisfaction from him while in their employment—from 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to 30<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. passed through his hands every day—lie had ten years' character when he came—he was allowed to go to any house in Paternoster Row for books.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-299" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-299" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-299" type="surname" value="AUSTIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-299" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES AUSTIN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">City Policeman</hi> 261). On 11th October I went to Messrs. Ascher and Co., 13, Bedford Street, Strand—I had a conversation with Mr. Ascher, and afterwards saw Ellis—I told him I should take him in custody for feloniously receiving two volumes of "Curtis's Greek Ety<lb></lb>mology" from the warehouse of Adams and Co., 32, Paternoster Row—he said "I bought the books, but did not know they were stolen"—I took him to the station, and found 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on him—going to the police court next morning he said "I bought the books of George Stewart, and paid 11<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for them, which was half the value"—he repeated that he did not know they were stolen.</p>
